# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bamischijf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bamischijf/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:bamischijf/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:bamischijf/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:bamischijf/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:bamischijf/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:bamischijf/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:bamischijf/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:bamischijf/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:bamischijf/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:bamischijf/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:bamischijf/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:bamischijf/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:bamischijf/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:bamischijf/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:bamischijf/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:bamischijf/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] An **apple pie** is a fruit pie in which the principal filling is apples.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] It is generally has shortcrust pastry both above and below the filling; the upper pastry may be solid or latticed (woven of crosswise strips).
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The bottom or pastry base may be baked separately (known as "blind-baking") to prevent it from getting soggy.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Tarte Tatin is baked with the pastry on top, but this is served the opposite way round with the fruit exposed.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] First recorded in the 14th century in England, apple pie recipes are now a standard part of cuisines in many countries where apples grow.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pie is a significant dessert in many countries, including the United Kingdom, Ireland, Sweden, Norway, Australia, Germany, New Zealand, and the United States.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] American apple pies are known to be considerably sweeter than their European cousins versions.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The fruit in an apple pie can be made with many different sorts of apples.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Common cooking apples include Braeburn, Gala, Cortland, Bramley, Empire, Northern Spy, Granny Smith, and McIntosh.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The fruit for the pie can be fresh, canned, or reconstituted from dried apples in the case of dried apple pie.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Dried or preserved apples were originally substituted only at times when fresh fruit was unavailable.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The basic ingredients of the filling are sugar, and an acidic ingredient like lemon juice.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] A thickener like eggs or corn starch may be added, while butter is added in the US.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Spices may be added like cinnamon or nutmeg.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Lemon juice which is used to prevent oxidation of the apples when macerating the filling.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Many older recipes call for honey in place of the then-expensive sugar.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Most apple pies use shortcrust pastry, however, the tarte Tatin is traditionally made with puff pastry, while the Greek milopita bougatsa uses filo pastry.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In the UK, custard is the traditional serving with apple pie, although cream, either whipped or poured, is also used.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pie in the US is often served *à la mode*, that is, topped with ice cream.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In another serving style originating in 17th century England, a piece of sharp cheddar or Wensleydale cheese is placed on top of a slice of the finished pie.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] This practice also occurs in the United States and Canada, particularly in regions with dairy farms, such as New England.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] A commercially prepared apple pie in the US is 52% water, 34% carbohydrates, 2% protein, and 11% fat (table).
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] A 100 g (3.5 oz) serving supplies 992 kilojoules (237 kilocalories) of food energy and 13% of the US recommended Daily Value of sodium, with no other micronutrients in significant amounts (table).
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The 14th century recipe collection the *Forme of Cury* gives a recipe including *good apples, good spices, figs, raisins and pears* in a *cofyn*, a casing of pastry.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Lattice pastry styles were found from the 17th century alongside the more traditional dome shaped pie crust.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In Yorkshire, *Wilfa apple cake* is served on St Wilfa's day, and although called a cake, it is made with shortcrust pastry topped with Wensleydale cheese.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In English-speaking countries, apple pie, often considered a comfort food, is eaten hot or cold, on its own or with cream, custard or ice cream.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pies are often sold in supermarkets and convenience stores as mini versions in multipacks.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Tarte aux pommes and tarte Tatin are both made with puff pastry.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The tarte Tatin is a tart in which the apples are caramelized in butter and sugar before the tart is baked.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The tarte is then served with the pastry served on the bottom exposing the caramelised apple.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Other variants include the Normandy tart, and Croustade.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In Germany, the word "kuchen" encompasses desserts that English speakers may call "pie", with apple pie coming under *Apfelkuchen*.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The traditional pastry based apple pie is known as *Gedeckter apfelkuchen* and is fully encased in pastry with the apples cooked in the oven.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Recipes for Dutch apple pie go back to the Middle Ages.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] An early Dutch language cookbook from 1514, *Een notabel boecxken van cokeryen* ("A notable little cookery book"), letterpress printed in Brussels by Thomas van der Noot, who may also have been the author, documents a recipe for *Appeltaerten* (modern Dutch *Appeltaarten* 'apple pies').
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] This early recipe was simple, requiring only shortcrust pastry, slices of especially soft apples with their skin and seeds removed, and *den selven deeghe daer die taerte af ghemaect es* (more of the same dough) on top.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] It was then baked in a typical Dutch oven.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Once baked, the top crust (except at the edges) would be cut out from the middle, after which the apple slices were potentially put through a sieve before the pie was stirred with a wooden spoon.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] At this point the book recommends adding several spices to the pie, namely: cardamom, ginger, cinnamon, nutmeg, clove, mace and powdered sugar.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Finally, after mixing the ingredients into the pie with cream, it is once again put into the oven to dry.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Traditional Dutch apple pie comes in two varieties, a crumb or streusel-top (*appelkruimeltaart*) and a lattice-top (*appeltaart*) style pie.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Both recipes are distinct in that they typically call for flavourings of cinnamon and lemon juice to be added and differ in texture, not taste.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Dutch apple pies may include ingredients such as full-cream butter, raisins and almond paste, in addition to ingredients such as apples and sugar, which they have in common with other recipes.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Both modern types have a shortcrust pastry on the bottom and around the edges.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The apples are usually a crisp and mildly tart variety such as Goudreinet or Elstar.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] It can be eaten warm or cold, sometimes with a dash of whipped cream or vanilla ice cream.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In Poland, *szarlotka* is regarded as apple pie.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] It has a shortcrust base, a filling of spiced shredded apple, and is either topped with more shortcrust pastry or a crumble mixture.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] There is a similar dish called *jabłecznik*, but this is considered a cake as it is not made with shortcrust pastry.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The Swedish style apple pie, *äppelpaj* is predominantly a variety of apple crumble, rather than a traditional pastry pie.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Often, breadcrumbs are used (wholly or partially) instead of flour, and sometimes rolled oats.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] It is usually flavoured with cinnamon and served with vanilla custard or ice cream.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pie was brought to the colonies by the English, the Dutch, and the Swedes during the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Two recipes for apple pie appear in America's first cookbook, *American Cookery* by Amelia Simmons, which was published in 1796.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The apple pie had to wait for the planting of European varieties, brought across the Atlantic, to become fruit-bearing apple trees, to be selected for their cooking qualities as there were no native apples except crabapples, which yield very small and sour fruit.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In the meantime, the colonists were more likely to make their pies, or "pasties", from meat, rather than fruit; and the main use for apples, once they were available, was in cider.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] However, there are American apple pie recipes, both manuscript and printed, from the 18th century.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple varieties are usually propagated by grafting, as clones, but in the New World, planting from seeds was more successful, leading to development of hundreds of new native varieties.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pie was a common food in 18th-century Delaware.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] As noted by the New Sweden historian Dr.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Israel Acrelius in a letter: "Apple pie is used throughout the whole year, and when fresh Apples are no longer to be had, dried ones are used.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The mock apple pie, made from crackers, was probably invented for use aboard ships, as it was known to the British Royal Navy as early as 1812.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The earliest known published recipes for mock apple pie date from the antebellum period of the 1850s.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In the 1930s, and for many years afterwards, Ritz Crackers promoted a recipe for mock apple pie using its product, along with sugar and various spices.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In the US, "Dutch apple pie" refers specifically to crumb-top variety known as appelkruimeltaart in the Netherlands.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Dried apple pie is prominent in the cuisine of the Pennsylvania Dutch, where it is known as *schnitz pie*.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Apple pie was one of the dishes that Rhode Island army officers ate for their Fourth of July celebrations during the Siege of Petersburg.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Although originating in England and eaten in Europe since long before the European colonisation of the Americas, apple pie as used in the phrase "as American as apple pie" describes something as being "typically American".
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] In the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, apple pie became a symbol of American prosperity and national pride.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] A newspaper article published in 1902 declared that "No pie-eating people can be permanently vanquished." The dish was also commemorated in the phrase "for Mom and apple pie"—supposedly the stock answer of American soldiers in World War II, whenever journalists asked why they were going to war.
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] Advertisers exploited the patriotic connection in the 1970s with the commercial jingle "baseball, hot dogs, apple pie and Chevrolet".
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] One out of five Americans surveyed (19%) prefer apple pie over all others, followed by pumpkin (13%) and pecan (12%).
[src:bamischijf/apple-pie] The unincorporated community of Pie Town, New Mexico, is named after apple pie.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The dish is believed to be based on Southern Chinese braised pork in soy sauce know in Indonesia as *babi taotjo* without the *taotjo* because of its unavailability in the past.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] However, it is more Indonesian in nature, because of the mild sweetness introduced by Indonesian *kecap manis* (sweet soy sauce).
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] It is sometimes prepared with a sweet chili sauce.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] In Bali, *babi kecap* is consumed at festivals such as Galungan and Nyepi.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The basic recipe, commonly used by Chinese Indonesians in their households, usually requires cuts of pork belly simmered with sweet soy sauce, spiced with garlic, shallot or onion, and a dash of salt.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The popular recipes employed elsewhere — from restaurants in Chinatown in Indonesia to Bali and the Netherlands, may include additional ingredients, such as lemongrass, ginger, tomato, shrimp paste, *salam* leaf (Indonesian bay leaf), white pepper, and red chilies.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] If sweet soy sauce is not available, it can be substituted with normal soy sauce mixed with ground palm sugar or brown sugar.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The less hot and spicy sweet pepper may be used to replace red chilies.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] Pork belly is usually the preferred cut of pork meat for *babi kecap*.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] However, other cuts of pork meat or offal may also be used in similar soy sauce-based recipes.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] Derivatives of this recipe that substitute the use of pork belly include *sengkel babi kecap*, which uses pig trotters, and *sekba*, which is a Chinese Indonesian pork offal stew that may also include pork liver, nose, tongue, ear, tripe, and intestines.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] It is very similar to another Indonesian favorite called *semur daging*, although *semur* is usually made of beef and potatoes with slightly different spices.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The chicken variant is called *ayam kecap* or Kip Smoor in Dutch.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] The word semur is a corruption of the Dutch word smoor (smoren is to braise in Dutch).
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] Originally Indonesian semur dishes are heated in butter instead of oil hinting at a Dutch origine.
[src:bamischijf/babi-kecap] Smoor can also be found in former Dutch colonies Sri Lanka and Malacca.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] Babi panggang Karo usually accompanied by clear pork bone soup, processed pork blood as dipping sauce, *daun ubi tumbuk* or mashed sweet potato leaves, and *tuak* or a drink of *nira* sap.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] The three dishes are served with plain rice and a sambal andaliman, made from fresh Sichuan pepper.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] In other parts of Indonesia and also Malaysia, where the Chinese are the main pork-eating population, *babi panggang* may simply be a local term for standard Chinese pork dishes—*babi panggang putih* is *siu yook* (燒肉), and *babi panggang merah* is Chinese *char siu* (叉燒).
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] In the Netherlands, *babi panggang* is a pork dish served with a tomato-based sauce.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] This Dutch/Indonesian/Chinese fusion dish is also known as *babi panggang speciaal* in the Netherlands, and the sauce as *speciaal saus* (lit.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] This fusion version of babi pangang became popular in the Netherlands and Flanders through so-called "Chinese-Indonesian restaurants", common in the Netherlands since the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] These restaurants are mainly owned and run by immigrants from Hong Kong.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] The dish consists of slices of crispy deep fried pork served on a bed of *acar campur* (a pickle-like a salad made with thinly sliced white cabbage and carrots of Indonesian origin; it is written *atjar tjampoer* in Dutch) over which a generous amount of the sauce is poured.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] The accompanying sauce for the Dutch version is similar to other tomato-based sweet and sour sauces common in Cantonese cuisine.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] Most recipes for this sauce include tomato puree, ketchup or fresh tomatoes, fresh or powdered ginger, water, vinegar, salt and a large amount of sugar.
[src:bamischijf/babi-panggang] Recipes may also include onion, garlic, soy sauce, sambal, fresh chili peppers, sherry or rice wine, broth, MSG, and cornstarch for thickening.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The noodles are known as *bakmi* in Indonesia, where they have been adapted to more closely align with the local tastes and into Javanese and Indo cuisine.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] *Bakmi* are between Chinese-style wheat noodles and Japanese udon in thickness, and there are several variants in Indonesia.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The name *bakmi* literally translates to "meat noodle".
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] In Indonesia, especially in large urban areas such as Jakarta, Medan, and Surabaya, there are many *warung* food stalls, restaurants, and eateries that serve this type of noodle dish, each specialising in different ingredients and toppings.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] Chinese influence is evident in Indonesian food such as *bakmi*, *mie ayam*, *pangsit*, *mie goreng*, and *kwetiau goreng*.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The words *mie* and *bami*, used in Dutch, come from *bakmi* and were introduced into the Dutch language during the Dutch colonial period in Indonesia.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] Indonesian food is very popular in the Netherlands, and *bami goreng* (fried *bakmi*) is a popular dish.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] In Thailand, wheat-based egg noodles are known as *bami*, which may be ordered as *bami nam* or *bami haeng* (egg noodles with soup and without soup respectively), and the noodles may be used in Chinese style stir-fried dishes.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] In the Philippines, a similar noodle dish is called pancit bam-i or pancit mami, where it is called *bam-i* in Cebuano Bisaya, or *mami/bami* in Tagalog (Filipino).
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The most common recipe of *bakmi* dish in Indonesia uses chicken meat as the majority of Indonesians are Muslims.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] Chicken noodle (Indonesian: *bakmie ayam or mie ayam*), *mie ayam* is wheat noodle topped with diced chicken meat seasoned in soy sauce.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] *Mie ayam* often accompanied with wonton (Indonesian: *pangsit*) either crispy fried or in soup, and also *bakso* (meatball).
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] *Bakmi ayam* is a popular Chinese Indonesian dish and ubiquitous in Indonesian cities, it can be served in a restaurant to a humble travelling cart.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The other popular Indonesian *bakmi* recipe is fried *bakmi* (Indonesian: *bakmie goreng* or Indonesian: *mie goreng*).
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] In Indonesia, the most common toppings are diced seasoned chicken with choy sum and fried wonton skin, to a more complete version served with fried or boiled wonton and *bakso* (meatballs).
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] The soup is served in a different bowl, and is added to the noodles by the individual diner according to taste.
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] Several notable Indonesian dishes developed from the original Chinese wheat noodle tradition includes *mie ayam* (chicken noodle) and *mie goreng* (stir fried noodle in sweet soy sauce).
[src:bamischijf/bakmi] *I fu mie* is *bakmi* that is first deep fried and then topped with a thickened gravy of vegetables and meat.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] Baozi are popular throughout China and have even made their way into the cuisines of many other countries through the Chinese diaspora.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] Baozi were originally called *mantou*, and may be related to the Central Asian dumpling manti.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] During the Western Jin Dynasty (266–316), Shu Xi wrote about dumplings and other wheat-based foods (at the time called *bing*), which he believed were from the Han dynasty (202 BC – 220 AD) or later.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] He described *mantou* as large meat-filled dumplings eaten at spring banquets.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] Other early sources mention the use of mantou in rituals.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] In the Tang dynasty, (618–907) mantou were small, made with leavened dough, and eaten as dianxin.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), *mantou* could have a variety of fillings (meat, poultry, fish, vegetables) and were said to be a common snack for students*.* During this period*,* baozi emerged as an alternate word for mantou, and subsequently mantou could also be used for unfilled buns.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] According to a legend first recorded in the Song dynasty, Zhuge Liang invented *mantou* to substitute for human heads in a sacrifice to gods.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] In the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty (1271–1368), court recipes for baozi and mantou included Central Asian elements with fillings such as lamb, onions, ginger, and chenpi.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] By the Qing dynasty (1664–1911), the words had settled into their modern meanings: *bing are* baked or steamed wheat cakes, *baozi* are buns with fillings, *mantou* are steamed buns without fillings, and *jiao* are thin-skinned dumplings with fillings.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] There is some regional variation in usage, mainly near Shanghai where small filled steamed dumplings are called mantou in Wu Chinese.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] There was a legend about a man named Zhuge Liang who was a military leader in China.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] For the barbarians to let him use this bridge, he had to sacrifice 50 of his soldiers and throw their heads into the river.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] Instead, in a clever deception, he fooled the barbarians by tossing 50 baos that looked like human heads into the river.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] In many Chinese cultures, these buns are a popular food, and widely available.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] While they can be eaten at any meal, baozi are often eaten for breakfast.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] They are also popular as a portable snack or meal.
[src:bamischijf/bakpau] The dish has also become commonplace throughout various regions of Northeast Asia with cultural and ethnic relationships, as well as Southeast Asia and outside Asia due to longstanding Chinese immigration.
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] The ingredients are quite similar to *sambal* hot chili paste.
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] However, unlike *sambal*, which is often treated as a separate dipping condiment, balado chili sauce is usually mixed and stir fried together with its main ingredients and treated as a dish.
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] Balado is suitable to be served with various types of seafood, such as fried prawns, squid, fish (whole or cutlets), as well as other ingredients, such as chicken, fried boiled eggs, fried beef, eggplant, and potatoes.
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] Because of its almost identical ingredients and technique, the term *balado* is often interchangeable with *sambal goreng* (lit.: "fried sambal").
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] Nevertheless, the term *balado* is more specifically referring to Minang cooking tradition, while *sambal goreng* refers to a more general Indonesian cuisine tradition.
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] In the Minang dialect, the term *balado* literally means "with chili" or "in chili", since *lado* means "chili pepper" in the Minang dialect (compared with the Indonesian word "berlada").
[src:bamischijf/balado-food] Hot and spicy balado has become an inspiration for a popular dangdut song, "Sambalado", sung by Ayu Tingting.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] A **bamischijf** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈbaːmisxɛif] ⓘ) is a Dutch snack consisting of a disc (Dutch: *schijf*) of *bami*, breaded and deep-fried.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] It is a Dutch modification of the Chinese-Indonesian noodle dish *bakmi goreng*.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] A nasischijf (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈnɑsisxɛif] ⓘ) is a similar dish made with *nasi goreng*.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The filling is prepared using a base of cooked bami.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The ingredients are similar to those for bami goreng: vegetables and meat, with Indonesian spices and sauces.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The noodles are packed as thick as possible so that the product's filling becomes dough-like in consistency.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] This mass is formed into a sausage roll, from which slices are cut.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] Much of this snack's production takes place in factories, where the product is prepared and then frozen, before being shipped to snackbars.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] Other varieties of *bamischijf* are usually named after their shape: *bamiblok* (bami block), *bamibal* (bami ball) and *bamihap* (bami bite).
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] Another variation is the *nasischijf* (nasi slice), which consists of nasi rather than bami.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The nasischijf (or nasibal when in ball form, or nasidisk in a disk shape) is a deep-fried snack consisting of nasi goreng encased in a breadcrumb coating.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] It is primarily popular in the Netherlands and Belgium.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] A similar snack, the bamischijf, replaces nasi goreng with bami goreng as the main ingredient.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The nasischijf originated from the Indonesian influence on Dutch cuisine, likely emerging in the 1950s as a way for toko (Indonesian-style stores) or snack bars to repurpose leftover rice.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] This influence reflects the broader incorporation of Indonesian flavors and ingredients into Dutch snacks following Indonesia's colonial history with the Netherlands.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The production process begins with cooking rice, which is then seasoned with spices to create the flavorful nasi goreng mixture.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] This rice mixture is formed into 'sausages' about 7 cm long, which are then sliced into rounds or balls and coated in breadcrumbs.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] The nasischijven are initially briefly deep-fried before being frozen.
[src:bamischijf/bamischijf] Once ready to serve, they are deep-fried again at cafeterias or snack bars.
